observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Unified effort of the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Assessor be exerted to locate the titles of these lands to properly safeguard the interest of the Municipality and the ownership thereof would be absolute and established for all legal intents and purposes;
Management to (i) prioritize the immediate registration and titling of unregistered/ untitled lots acquired through purchase or donation in the name of the Municipality, thus, allocate funds for incidental expenses to be incurred in the registration and titling of lots;
Reconciliation of records and documents on file between the Office of the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Assessor should be done and updated regularly to ascertain that the recorded balance in the books of the Municipality is valid and accurate;
The Municipal Accountant to maintain the RPLC which records the property description, location, acquisition cost, additions, and disposition of real properties owned by the Municipality and should support the Land account balance in the financial statements; and
Municipal Planning and Development Council ensure that improvements and public infrastructures are constructed on the lot absolutely owned by the Municipality.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Undertake the proper disposal of unserviceable properties through its disposal committee in accordance with Section 79 of PD 1445, to prevent further deterioration and loss of additional income;
Appraisal committee to determine the reasonable price for unserviceable properties that are found to be valuable and maybe sold at public auction or private sale, as the case maybe;
The GSO to update the IIRUP after disposal of unserviceable properties and furnish a copy thereof to the Municipal Accountant and Audit Team; and
Henceforth, the Municipal Accountant draw a journal entry voucher to derecognize/drop from the books of accounts the disposed unserviceable properties based on the IIRUP submitted by the GSO.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Limit the practice of serving meals and snacks during meetings particularly those events which are considered among the regular functions or normal activities of the Municipality. Instead, focus the utilization of the government funds for purposes which are more beneficial to the constituents;
Observe economy and austerity measures in the use of government funds which are intended for public purpose;
The Municipal Budget Officer properly charge or limit such expenditures against appropriations for Representation Expenses, Extraordinary and Miscellaneous Expenses, or Discretionary Fund, which are provided for the purpose; and
The Municipal Accountant ensure the completeness of required documents to support the propriety of payments.

We recommended and the Management agreed to direct the:
BAC to use the prescribed format of the Annual Procurement Plan and ensure that vital information is provided thereto in accordance with (GBBP) Resolution No. 20-2015 dated July 16, 2015;
Offices concerned to properly plan their procurement activities through the preparation of the Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) which contains all the anticipated materials, services, goods, civil works requirements and the BAC Secretariat to consolidate the same into an Annual Procurement Plan;
BAC to undertake procurement in bulk to save time, costs and manpower hours using public bidding as the primary mode of procurement and discontinue the practice of procuring supplies and equipment through shopping or small value procurement unless the conditions in Section 52.1 and 53.9 of the Revised IRR of RA 9184 are met; and
BAC, TWG and Secretariat to avoid/stop splitting of contracts in compliance with the revised IRR of RA No. 9184.

Perform the necessary reconciliation with the GSIS to trace the unremitted balances amounting to ₱0.880 million which have accrued for several years, for proper disposition;
Improve monitoring systems to ensure that all contributions and loans withheld during the period are remitted intact moving forward; and
Maintain subsidiary ledgers to keep track of contributions and loan deductions withheld and remitted per individual employee.

Review their respective records (GL and Cashbook) to account for the difference of ₱126,465.09 by comparing each other’s entries in their respective records;

	Effect the necessary adjustments in their respective records to come up with the accurate Cash-Local Treasury account balance; 

Henceforth, conduct thorough periodic reconciliation between their respective records so that errors in recording will be corrected/adjusted at the earliest possible time; and

Adhere with the periodic submission of accounts and financial reports to the Office of the Auditor so that errors or deficiencies that may be found in audit could be early communicated to the concerned personnel.

Locate/secure a copy of the Deed of Donation. Henceforth, prioritize the immediate registration and titling of the donated lot in the name of the Municipality and allocate funds for the purpose;

Stop any construction/improvements of public infrastructures on the subject lot pending the actual transfer of title to the Municipality;

Provide budgetary allocation for the processing of DOH-LTO and installation of electrical and water connections;

Require the Rural Health Unit (RHU) personnel to immediately apply for the necessary authorizations, licenses, permits and other requirements from the Department of Health, and the Municipal Engineer to fast track the application and processing of electrical and water connections for the project to become fully operational and to serve the very purpose for which it was implemented; and

Assign personnel to conduct routine maintenance and inspection activities in order to prevent undue deterioration, wear and tear to the facility pending the obtainment of the requirements to operate.

The Local Chief Executive negotiate with the owners of the lots used as sites for the construction of SALINTUBIG Projects for the execution of the Deed of Donations in favor of the Municipality or concerned barangays;

The Designated Property Officer and Municipal Assessor prioritize the immediate registration and titling of unregistered/ untitled lots acquired through purchase or donation in the name of the Municipality, thus, allocate funds for incidental expenses to be incurred in the registration and titling of lots; and

The Municipal Planning and Development Council ensure that improvements and public infrastructures are constructed on the lot absolutely owned by the Municipality.

Prepare an aging schedule of all the individual accounts composing the Accounts Payable and Other Payables account and reconcile discrepancies in the schedule;

Contact the suppliers to confirm the amounts which the LGU is still liable to pay;

In the absence of any possible claims, revert these Accounts/Other Payables to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund of the LGU/national government, pursuant to Section 98 of P.D. No. 1445; and

Draw out the necessary journal entries and furnish the Audit Team with the JEV.

The GSO conduct ocular inspection of all properties and equipment and update the IIRUP to cover all unserviceable properties from CY 2020 up to the most recent date;

Management create a disposal committee who will undertake the proper disposal of unserviceable properties in accordance with Section 79 of PD No. 1445; and

	Create an appraisal committee who will determine the reasonable price for unserviceable properties that are found to be valuable and maybe sold at public auction or private sale, as the case maybe.

The Local Chief Executive negotiate with the owners of the lots used as sites for the construction of SALINTUBIG Projects for the execution of the Deed of Donations in favor of the Municipality or concerned barangays;

The Designated Property Officer and Municipal Assessor prioritize the immediate registration and titling of unregistered/untitled lots acquired through purchase or donation in the name of the Municipality, thus, allocate funds for incidental expenses to be incurred in the registration and titling of lots; and

	The Municipal Planning and Development Council ensure that improvements and public infrastructures are constructed on the lot absolutely owned by the Municipality.

Prepare an aging schedule of all the individual accounts composing the Accounts Payable and Other Payables account and reconcile discrepancies in the schedule;

Contact the suppliers to confirm the amounts which the LGU is still liable to pay;

	In the absence of any possible claims, revert these Accounts/Other Payables to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund of the LGU/national government, pursuant to Section 98 of P.D. No. 1445; and

Draw out the necessary journal entries and furnish the Audit Team with the JEV.

We recommended the following:

a. The MDC realign the residual balances of completed projects to other viable developmental projects, subject to the approval of the Sangguniang Bayan;

b. The MDC conduct intensive review of the continuing projects under the 20% DF to determine if the PPAs are still part of the vital needs of the Municipality particularly for suspended projects including the road opening for Camanga, Camalig, Bantao project which has existing unused fuel, otherwise reprogram the identified PPAs to priority PPAs;

c. The MDC identify and indicate specific PPAs with program of works already and allocate budget accordingly for each area of developmental project; and

d. The BAC, Municipal Engineer, MPDC and MDC properly plan and schedule all procurement activities pertaining to development projects to pave the way for their timely implementation and completion.

It is recommended that Management;

a. Direct the Municipal Accountant to demand the liquidation of cash advances for employees still connected with the agency, otherwise, imposed sanctions by withholding of amount in the salary and other benefits of the employees:

b. Institute appropriate efforts to collect on the unliquidated cash advances, specifically for employees no longer connected with the Municipality by coordinating with the respective mother offices in locating the non-organic personnel with unliquidated cash advances and demand immediate settlement thereof, and

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Review their respective records (GL and Cashbook) to account for the difference of ₱126,465.09 by comparing each other’s entries in their respective records;
Effect the necessary adjustments in their respective records to come up with the accurate Cash-Local Treasury account balance;
Henceforth, conduct thorough periodic reconciliation between their respective records so that errors in recording will be corrected/adjusted at the earliest possible time; and
Adhere with the periodic submission of accounts and financial reports to the Office of the Auditor so that errors or deficiencies that may be found in audit could be early communicated to the concerned personnel.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Locate/secure a copy of the Deed of Donation. Henceforth, prioritize the immediate registration and titling of the donated lot in the name of the Municipality and allocate funds for the purpose;
Stop any construction/improvements of public infrastructures on the subject lot pending the actual transfer of title to the Municipality;
Provide budgetary allocation for the processing of DOH-LTO and installation of electrical and water connections;
Require the Rural Health Unit (RHU) personnel to immediately apply for the necessary authorizations, licenses, permits and other requirements from the Department of Health, and the Municipal Engineer to fast track the application and processing of electrical and water connections for the project to become fully operational and to serve the very purpose for which it was implemented; and
Assign personnel to conduct routine maintenance and inspection activities in order to prevent undue deterioration, wear and tear to the facility pending the obtainment of the requirements to operate.

We recommended to the Management:
Constitute the Inventory Committee with adequate members, including a representative from the Accounting and Property Division/Unit who will prepare a Physical Inventory Plan containing the specific assignments/duties of the committee members from start up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to prioritize the completion of physical count of PPEs and prepare the RPCPPE;
Instruct the Accounting Unit to prepare the necessary adjusting entries, if any, among others, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Require the Accounting Office and Property Division/Unit to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts to be considered as the correct balance of the agency’s PPEs to comply with Item 5.12 of COA Circular 2020-006; and
Direct the Property Division/Unit to prepare and issue the ICS for those items reclassified from PPE to semi-expandable properties.

We recommended that Management:
The implementation of delayed 20% DF projects to enhance the delivery of essential services to the constituents;
Evaluate the viability of projects which were not implemented during the year to determine the cause/s of their non-implementation. If not viable, consider the reprogramming of said funds to another projects;
Direct the Local Development Council and the Municipal Engineer to closely monitor and pursue the timely and full implementation of all development projects; and
Prepare the Report on Government Projects, Programs, or Activities (PPAs) under 20% DF to include all projects funded by national government agencies with complete data and information and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor.

The Local Chief Executive (LCE) to: (i) require the Inventory Committee to conduct annual physical inventory of all PPE items, prepare the required RPCPPE and a copy thereof shall be submitted to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of the following year; and (ii) direct the Municipal Appraisal and Disposal Committee to come up with reasonable valuation/appraisal of PPE items found at station and those acquired through donation which shall be recognized in the books of the Municipality in accordance with the guidelines set forth in PPSAS 17;

Property Cards for each group of PPEs shall be maintained by the Municipal General Services Officer which shall be reconciled regularly with the PPELC maintained by the Municipal Accountant; and

The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entries to set up the correct depreciation reckoned from the date of acquisition or completion of the assets up to the present by debiting prior period adjustment and crediting accumulated depreciation and ensure monthly recognition of depreciation expense of all depreciable PPE accounts.

At the beginning of the year, the Municipal Treasurer’s Office furnish the Municipal Accounting Office of a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year;

The Municipal Accountant use the Real Property Tax Account Register/ Taxpayer’s index card, Certified List of Taxpayers and Tax Due and Demandable submitted by the Municipal Treasurer’s Office as basis for setting up the RPT/SET receivables and deferred credits at the beginning of the year;

The Municipal Accounting Office maintain subsidiary ledgers for RPT/SET Receivables and Deferred Income accounts to facilitate easy reconciliation and monitoring of the balances; and 

Encourage the involvement of barangay officials in the tax campaign to reach out to a wider area and intensify tax collections thru formulating strategies to improve collection of real property taxes.

Carefully evaluate before granting/approving the contractor’s request for work suspensions and contract time extensions and demand from the contractor the submission of required documents and records that would justify the reason for such request which should be among those cited in Section 10 and 11 of Annex “E” of the RIRR of RA. No. 9184;

Require the BAC Chairman to furnish the Auditor of every revision made to the contract such as contract time extension due to suspension orders, extra work orders or variation orders for appropriate review and evaluation; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to: (i) ensure the completeness of supporting documents attached to the disbursement vouchers for infrastructure projects prior to approval and payment of any claims by the contractor; and (ii) compute and impose liquidated damages at least equal to one-tenth of one percent (0.001) of the cost of the unperformed portion for every day of delay relative to contractor’s claims for infrastructure projects with invalid and unsubstantiated requests for work suspensions and contract time extensions.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Budget Officer to submit the SAAOB for the continuing appropriations for audit purposes;

Require the Municipal Engineer to submit the accomplishment report for the projects funded under the continuing appropriations to allow the Audit Team evaluate the same;

Pursue improved practices in programming, prioritizing and implementing programs and projects to maximize the implementation of development projects to ensure that optimum benefits are derived by the greater number of its constituents;

Meticulously and judiciously review and evaluate projects before its inclusion in the Local Development Fund and Annual Investment Plan and provide realistic timelines for its completion;

We recommended that Management require:

The MDRRMO to prepare and submit the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF through the LDRRMC and Local Development Council (LDC) to the COA Auditor on or before the 15th day after the end of each month;

The Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking disbursement vouchers for post-audit by the Audit Team;

Further, to maintain the appropriate subsidiary records of all transactions and to use back up devices such as USB/data traveler to facilitate recovery of records and documents in case that these are lost/damaged due to force majeure; and

The submission of the necessary Appropriation Ordinance authorizing the realignment of the funds of the LGU for COVID-19 response supported by the following: (i) certification of source/s of funds available for appropriations as certified under oath jointly by the local treasurer and the local accountant and attested to by the LCE; (ii) the items of appropriations affected; and (iii) the reason for the change.

We recommended that Management:

Require the immediate submission of the afore-cited lacking documents, otherwise, the non-submission of these documents shall warrant the issuance of Notice of Suspension/Disallowance; 

Stop payment of salary wages of utility workers assigned in the Division Office or in other areas other than the elementary and secondary schools that are being charged against SEF;

Strictly comply with the provision of Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445 to protect the interest of the government and to prevent unwarranted disbursements of public funds.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendations for Management to:

Pursue the immediate approval of the 10- Year SWM Plan as required under RA No. 9003; 

Persevere in pursuing the acquisition of solid waste disposal site and waste management facilities in accordance with Sections 41 and 42 of RA No. 9003;

Cause the immediate installation of electrical connection in the site of the Cluster MRF in order that it become operational; and

Intensify the conduct of SWM information dissemination in the barangays.

We also recommended for Management to make representations with the Sangguniang Bayan for the enactment of an ordinance regarding fines, penalties and sanctions on violations of rules and regulations on SWM.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit on a monthly basis the Report on Utilization of DRRMF;
Prepare and submit the pertinent registries and subsidiary ledgers in compliance with the accounting and reporting guidelines of DRRMF;
Reconcile the balances presented in the Report on Utilization of DRRMF with the registries and subsidiary ledgers and correct the report, as necessary;
Ensure proper documentation of approval for the changes in the utilization of funds and implementation of projects not indicated in the approved budget/LDRRMP/LDRRMFIP; and
Maintain sufficient stockpile of relief goods and ensure that it is properly monitored and kept in a safe storage area.

The Local Chief Executive (LCE) to: (i) require the Inventory Committee to conduct annual physical inventory of all PPE items, prepare the required RPCPPE and a copy thereof shall be submitted to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of the following year; and (ii) direct the Municipal Appraisal and Disposal Committee to come up with reasonable valuation/appraisal of PPE items found at station and those acquired through donation which shall be recognized in the books of the Municipality in accordance with the guidelines set forth in PPSAS 17;
Property Cards for each group of PPEs shall be maintained by the Municipal General Services Officer which shall be reconciled regularly with the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELC) maintained by the Municipal Accountant; and
The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entries to set up the correct depreciation reckoned from the date of acquisition or completion of the assets up to the present by debiting prior period adjustment and crediting accumulated depreciation and ensure monthly recognition of depreciation expense of all depreciable PPE accounts.

Carefully evaluate before granting/approving the contractor’s request for work suspensions and contract time extensions and demand from the contractor the submission of required documents and records that would justify the reason for such request which should be among those cited in Section 10 and 11 of Annex “E” of the Revised IRR of RA. No. 9184;
The BAC Chairman furnish the Auditor of every revision made to the contract such as contract time extension due to suspension orders, extra work orders or variation orders for appropriate review and evaluation; and
The Municipal Accountant to: (i) ensure the completeness of supporting documents attached to the disbursement vouchers for infrastructure projects prior to approval and payment of any claims by the contractor; and (ii) compute and impose liquidated damages at least equal to one-tenth of one percent of the cost of the unperformed portion for every day of delay relative to contractor’s claims for infrastructure projects with invalid and unsubstantiated requests for work suspensions and contract time extensions.

The Bids and Awards Committee and the Municipal Engineer properly plan and schedule all procurement activities pertaining to development projects to pave the way for their timely implementation and completion;
Management implement immediately all the projects under the continuing appropriations, otherwise, unimplemented PPAs which are no longer feasible should be considered for immediate realignment subject to budgetary rules or reverted back to the unappropriated surplus of the 20%  Development  Fund   for   reprogram/re-appropriation   to   other development projects; and
The Local Development  Council,  Municipal  Planning  and  Development Coordinator and the Municipal Engineer to: (i) regularly  monitor  the status of project implementation so that necessary  interventions  may be introduced at the earliest time; and  (ii)  reprogram/re-align  the accumulated savings  totaling  ₱4.795  million  to  other  development  projects which should be embodied in the local development  plan,  and medium-term and annual investment program of the succeeding year.

Analyze, review, reconcile and monitor all booked receivables and adjust accordingly to ensure that only valid receivables are recorded in the books;
Analyze all the Receivables that are dormant, long outstanding and unsubstantiated for proper disposition and recognition;
Maintain subsidiary ledgers and supporting documents to substantiate the recorded balance of Receivable accounts;
Send demand letters to accountable officers, Non-Government Organizations (NGOs)/People’s Organization (POs) and National Government Agencies (NGAs) who are recipients of various fund releases from the Municipality to immediately liquidate or settle the funds received. Otherwise, cause the refund of the outstanding balances due them; and
Exhaust all possible remedies to recover records/documents available to validate claims or else file a request for authority to write-off of dormant receivables accounts to the COA Audit Team Leader in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

The Local Chief Executive (LCE) require the MDRRM Council to prepare and submit the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Investment Plan (LDRRMIP) indicating the (i) detailed PPAs and the corresponding appropriation classified as either MOOE or Capital Outlay; and (ii) under a separate caption, the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years for ease of monitoring of project implementation and evaluation;
The MDRRMC and Municipal Budget Officer ensure that the LDRRMF be strictly utilized for the implementation of projects and activities for disaster prevention and mitigation, preparedness, response and rehabilitation, and recovery; and
The Municipal Accountant investigate the discrepancy amounting to ₱8,827.88 and prepare the necessary adjustments in order to reflect the correct balance of Trust Liabilities-DRRM account in the financial statements.

Direct the NGOs/POs and the Municipal Accountant to submit to Commission on Audit a Status Report on the Implementation of the Project and a satisfactory written explanation as to why liquidations of funds transferred to NGOs/POs remained outstanding in the books of accounts over the last four years;
Demand from the NGOs/POs to return the unutilized fund/excess amount of funds to the Municipality; and
Ensure that succeeding fund releases to NGOs/POs strictly adhere to the rules and regulations embodied in COA Circular Nos. 2007-001 and 2012-001.

Management ensure that only necessary expenditures are incurred, observe prudence and fiscal restraint in utilizing government funds which are intended for public purpose;
Expenses for catering services incurred during meetings and conferences where participants thereto are all LGU personnel in the performance of their regular duties/functions should not be charged to government funds;
Submit justification why the incurrence of the foregoing expenses should not be disallowed in audit, otherwise, refund the total amount which are considered unnecessary expenditures; and
Constantly be guided by COA Circular No. 2012-003 dated October 29, 2012 and strictly adhere thereto to avoid incurrence of irregular, unnecessary, excessive, extravagant and unconscionable expenditures.

For the deficiencies observed, we recommended for Management to:

Require the concerned personnel who are permissible to render overtime service with pay to submit request for authority to render overtime together with overtime work program;

Oblige the concerned personnel/head to submit quantified overtime accomplishment duly signed by the employee and supervisor together with the approved daily time record upon the processing of overtime pay;

Further, for Management to demand from the Municipal Treasurer the refund of the excess of ₱15,128.00 in overtime pay; otherwise, this warrant the issuance of audit disallowance.

We recommended the following:
Require the Municipal Accountant to effect the necessary adjustments to recognize a liability representing the unutilized balance of the BGCM fund amounting to ₱26,450.00 and maintain a separate subsidiary ledger in compliance with LBC No. 125 dated April 7, 2020;

Direct the Municipal Accountant and Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to submit the required documents to the Office of the Auditor for further evaluation of the transactions pursuant to Section 4(6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and GPPB Circular No. 01-2020 dated April 6, 2020;

Replenish the amount of ₱26,450.00 representing inappropriate charges against the BGCM fund which shall form part of the unutilized balance for re-appropriation to other allowable PPAs for COVID-19 response, otherwise, the remaining balance, if any, shall be reverted to the National Treasury after the lifting of the State of Calamity;

Ensure that only authorized COVID-19 related PPAs shall be charged against the BGCM fund as enumerated under DBM Local Budget Circular No. 125 dated April 7, 2020; and

	Require the BAC to strictly comply with the posting requirement of GPPB Circular No. 01-2020 dated April 6, 2020 for information purposes and to promote transparency and accountability in the conduct of Emergency Procurement under the Bayanihan Act.

We recommended that:

	The Municipal Assessor furnish the Municipal Treasurer on or before the 31st day of December of each year, an assessment roll containing a list of all real property, whether taxable or exempt, located within the territorial jurisdiction of the Municipal Government of Malinao, Aklan and a list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed or reassessed and the values of such properties;

The Municipal Treasurer prepare a duly certified list showing the name of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant to serve as the basis in setting up the beginning balance of RPT/SET Receivable in the books of accounts. In such manner, the related receivable account and deferred liability will be presented fairly in the financial statements;

	The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant conduct reconciliation of records to establish a realistic balance of receivables for the RPT Taxes and SET Taxes so that necessary adjustment(s) in the books of accounts can be effected for a more realistic presentation of the balances in the financial statements;

The Municipal Treasurer religiously update the individual Real Property Tax Account Register (RPTAR) or Taxpayer’s Index Card every time a payment is received from the taxpayer which shall serve as the basis in the preparation of the List of Delinquent Real Property Taxpayers as of the end of the year, the total of which shall equal the RPT/SET Receivable at year end; and

	The Local Chief Executive (LCE), Municipal Treasurer and other concerned Municipal Officials exert concerted efforts to intensify collections of long outstanding RPT and SET Receivables including the interest thereon so that more development programs may be implemented for the benefit of the constituents.

